Problem:
A solid right prism $ABCDEF$ has a height of $16,$ as shown. Also, its bases are equilateral triangles with side length $12.$ Points $X,$ $Y,$ and $Z$ are the midpoints of edges $AC,$ $BC,$ and $DC,$ respectively. A part of the prism above is sliced off with a straight cut through points $X,$ $Y,$ and $Z.$ Determine the surface area of solid $CXYZ,$ the part that was sliced off.  [asy]
pair A, B, C, D, E, F, X, Y, Z;
A=(0,0);
B=(12,0);
C=(6,-6);
D=(6,-22);
E=(0,-16);
F=(12,-16);
X=(A+C)/2;
Y=(B+C)/2;
Z=(C+D)/2;
draw(A--B--C--A--E--D--F--B--C--D);
draw(X--Y--Z--X, dashed);
label("$A$", A, NW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, SW);
label("$F$", F, SE);
label("$X$", X, SW);
label("$Y$", Y, SE);
label("$Z$", Z, SE);
label("12", (A+B)/2, dir(90));
label("16", (B+F)/2, dir(0));
[/asy]

generated_answer:
We begin by finding the heights of $\triangle ABC$ and $\triangle CDX.$  Let $H$ be the foot of the altitude from $C$ to $\overline{AB},$ and let $H'$ be the foot of the altitude from $D$ to $\overline{CX}.$  Then $CH = 6 \sqrt{3}$ and $DH' = 3 \sqrt{3}.$

[asy]
size(200);
pair A, B, C, D, E, F, X, Y, Z, H, Hp;
A=(0,0);
B=(12,0);
C=(6,-6);
D=(6,-22);
E=(0,-16);
F=(12,-16);
X=(A+C)/2;
Y=(B+C)/2;
Z=(C+D)/2;
H=foot(C,A,B);
Hp=foot(D,C,X);
draw(A--B--C--A--E--D--F--B--C--D);
draw(C--H,red);
draw(D--Hp,red);
draw(X--Y--Z--X, dashed);
label("$A$", A, NW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, SW);
label("$F$", F, SE);
label("$X$", X, SW);
label("$Y$", Y, SE);
label("$Z$", Z, SE);
label("$H$", H, NE, red);
label("$H'$", Hp, NE, red);
label("12", (A+B)/2, dir(90));
label("16", (B+F)/2, dir(0));
[/asy]

Then by the Pythagorean Theorem, $AH = BH = \sqrt{12^2 - (6 \sqrt{3})^2} = 6 \sqrt{3},$ so $\triangle ABC$ is equilateral with height $6 \sqrt{3},$ and $\triangle CDX$ is a $30^\circ$-$60^\circ$-$90^\circ$ triangle with height $3 \sqrt{3}.$

The surface area of $CXYZ$ is then $XY \cdot CH' + CZ \cdot DH' + \frac{1}{2} (CY + XZ) \cdot CZ.$  We have that $XY = \frac{1}{2} AB = 6 \sqrt{3},$ $CH' = 6,$ $CZ = 6,$ $DH' = 3 \sqrt{3},$ $CY = CZ = 6,$ and $XZ = CD - CZ = 6 \sqrt{3} - 6.$  Hence, the surface area of $CXYZ$ is
\begin{align*}
&6 \sqrt{3} \cdot 6 + 6 \cdot 3 \sqrt{3} + \frac{1}{2} (6 + 6 \sqrt{3} - 6) \cdot 6 \\
&= 36 \sqrt{3} + 27 \sqrt{3} + 18 \\
&= \boxed{63 \sqrt{3} + 18}.
\end{align*}

Let $P$ and $Q$ be the midpoints of $\overline{AD}$ and $\overline{EF},$ respectively. Then $XP$ and $ZQ$ are medians of $\triangle ACD$ and $\triangle CDF,$ respectively, so $CXYZ$ is a parallelogram. [asy]
pair A, B, C, D, E, F, X, Y, Z, P, Q;
A=(0,0);
B=(12,0);
C=(6,-6);
D=(6,-22);
E=(0,-16);
F=(12,-16);
X=(A+C)/2;
Y=(B+C)/2;
Z=(C+D)/2;
P=(A+D)/2;
Q=(E+F)/2;
draw(A--B--C--A--E--D--F--B--C--D);
draw(X--Y--Z--X);
draw(C--P);
draw(C--Q);
label("$A$", A, NW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, SW);
label("$F$", F, SE);
label("$X$", X, SW);
label("$Y$", Y, SE);
label("$Z$", Z, SE);
label("$P$", P, W);
label("$Q$", Q, E);
label("12", (A+B)/2, dir(90));
label("16", (B+F)/2, dir(0));
[/asy] We know that $PX = \frac{1}{2} AD = 12$ and $CQ = \frac{1}{2} EF = 8,$ so $CZ = 16 - PQ = 16 - \sqrt{12^2 - 8^2} = 4\sqrt{5}.$

[asy]
size(7cm);
pair A, B, C, D, E, F, X, Y, Z, P, Q;
A=(0,0);
B=(12,0);
C=(6,-6);
D=(6,-22);
E=(0,-16);
F=(12,-16);
X=(A+C)/2;
Y=(B+C)/2;
Z=(C+D)/2;
P=(A+D)/2;
Q=(E+F)/2;
draw(A--B--C--A--E--D--F--B--C--D);
draw(X--Y--Z--X);
draw(C--P);
draw(C--Q);
label("$A$", A, NW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, SW);
label("$F$", F, SE);
label("$X$", X, SW);
label("$Y$", Y, SE);
label("$Z$", Z, SE);
label("$P$", P, W);
label("$Q$", Q, E);
label("12", (A+B)/2, dir(90));
label("16", (B+F)/2, dir(0));
label("$8$", (C+Q)/2, E);
label("$12$", (X+P)/2, W);
label("$4\sqrt{5}$", (C+Z)/2, NW);
[/asy]

Also, $CY = \frac{1}{2} BC = 6\sqrt{3}$ and $XY = \frac{1}{2} AB = 6\sqrt{3},$ so the area of parallelogram $CXYZ$ is $CY \cdot CZ = (6\sqrt{3})(4\sqrt{5}) = \boxed{12\sqrt{15}}.$

We can split the pyramid into three parts: a pyramid with apex $C,$ a pyramid with apex $D,$ and a frustum of a pyramid with apex $B$ and top base $CXYZ$ (which is the part we want to find the surface area of). The first two pyramids have the same volume, so we just need to find the surface area of one of them and double it. The height of the pyramid is $16,$ and the base is an equilateral triangle with side length $12,$ so its area is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}\cdot 12^2 = 36\sqrt{3}.$ By the Pythagorean Theorem, the slant height of the pyramid is $\sqrt{16^2+6^2} = 2\sqrt{205},$ so the lateral area of the pyramid is $\frac{1}{2}\cdot 12\cdot 2\sqrt{205} = 12\sqrt{205}.$ Therefore, the surface area of the two pyramids is $2\cdot 12\sqrt{205} = 24\sqrt{205}.$

[asy]
import three;
triple A, B, C, D, E, F, X, Y, Z;
A=(0,0,0);
B=(12,0,0);
C=(6,-6,0);
D=(6,-22,0);
E=(0,-16,0);
F=(12,-16,0);
X=(A+C)/2;
Y=(B+C)/2;
Z=(C+D)/2;
draw(A--B--C--A--E--D--F--B--C--D--Z--Y--X--Z,dashed);
draw(A--X);
draw(B--Y);
draw(D--Z);
draw(C--X--Y--Z--C,dashed);
label("$A$", A, NW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, SW);
label("$F$", F, SE);
label("$X$", X, SE);
label("$Y$", Y, NE);
label("$Z$", Z, S);
label("12", (A+B)/2, dir(90));
label("16", (B+F)/2, dir(0));
draw((0,0,0)--(0,-16,0)--(12,-16,0)--(12,0,0)--cycle);
draw((0,0,0)--(6,-6,-16)--(12,0,-16)--cycle);
draw((0,-16,0)--(6,-22,-16)--(12,-16,-16)--cycle);
draw((12,0,0)--(6,-6,-16)--(12,-16,-16)--(12,-16,0),dashed);
[/asy]

The frustum has height $16,$ top base $CXYZ,$ and bottom base $BC,$ which is an equilateral triangle with side length $12.$ The area of the bottom base is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}\cdot 12^2 = 36\sqrt{3},$ and the area of the top base is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}\cdot 6^2 = 9\sqrt{3}.$ The slant height of the frustum is $\sqrt{16^2+6^2} = 2\sqrt{205},$ so the lateral area of the frustum is \[\frac{1}{2}\cdot (12+6)\cdot 2\sqrt{205} = 18\sqrt{205}.\]Therefore, the surface area of the solid $CXYZ$ is $9\sqrt{3}+18\sqrt{205}.$

Thus, the total surface area of the solid $CXYZ$ is $2\cdot 24\sqrt{205} + 9\sqrt{3}+18\sqrt{205} = \boxed{27\sqrt{3} + 60\sqrt{205}}.$

The slice $CXYZ$ is a triangle with side lengths $6,$ $6\sqrt{3},$ and $\sqrt{33}.$ This can be seen by observing that $CX = 6,$ $CY = CZ = 6\sqrt{3},$ and $YZ = \sqrt{33}.$

[asy]
pair X, Y, Z;
X = (0,0);
Y = (1,1.732);
Z = (3,0);
draw(X--Y--Z--X);
label("$X$", X, SW);
label("$Y$", Y, N);
label("$Z$", Z, SE);
label("$6$", (X+Z)/2, S);
label("$6\sqrt{3}$", (Y+Z)/2, NE);
label("$6\sqrt{3}$", (X+Y)/2, NW);
label("$\sqrt{33}$", (X+Y)/2 + 0.2*dir(60), dir(60));
[/asy]

Thus, the area of $CXYZ$ is given by Heron's formula:
\begin{align*}
[\triangle CXYZ] &= \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}(6+6\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{33})(6+6\sqrt{3}-6)(6+6\sqrt{3}-\sqrt{33})(6-\sqrt{3})} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}(6+6\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{33})(18\sqrt{3}-\sqrt{33})(6-\sqrt{3})} \\
&= 12\sqrt{3} - 6\sqrt{11}.
\end{align*}

The surface area of $CXYZ$ is just the sum of the areas of the three faces that make up the slice, which is $\boxed{72\sqrt{3} - 36\sqrt{11}}.$

We can find the surface area of the whole prism, and then subtract the surface area of the part of the prism that is not $CXYZ.$

The surface area of the whole prism is the sum of the areas of the three pairs of congruent parallelograms: $$2(12)(16)+2\left(\frac{1}{2}(12)(12)\right)+2\left(\frac{1}{2}(12)(12)\right)=576.$$The part of the prism that is not $CXYZ$ is a smaller right prism, which has a height of $8$ and two trapezoidal faces.  The height of each trapezoidal face is $6,$ and the bases are $6$ and $12,$ so the area of each trapezoidal face is $\frac{1}{2}(6+12)(6)=54.$  Thus, the total surface area of the two trapezoidal faces is $108.$

Therefore, the surface area of $CXYZ$ is $576-108=\boxed{468}.$

