Let $AB = 1000$ and $AD = 2009.$  Then $AM = 17$ and $AN = 34.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M, N, P;

A = (0,0);
B = (10,0);
D = (4,6);
C = B + D;
M = interp(A,B,17/1000);
N = interp(A,D,17/2009);
P = extension(A,C,M,N);

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(M--P--N);

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, NE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
label("$N$", N, W);
label("$P$", P, NE);
[/asy]

Since $ABCD$ is a parallelogram, $AC$ bisects both $\angle BAD$ and $\angle BCD.$  Let $\theta = \angle BAD.$  Then $\angle BCD = \theta,$ so $\triangle BPC$ is isosceles, and $PC = BC.$

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABD,$
\[BD^2 = AB^2 + AD^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot AD \cdot \cos \theta.\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $APN,$
\begin{align*}
AP^2 &= AN^2 + NP^2 - 2 \cdot AN \cdot NP \cdot \cos \angle PNA \\
&= AN^2 + NP^2 - 2 \cdot AN \cdot NP \cdot \cos (\theta/2).
\end{align*}By the Law of Cosines on triangle $BPM,$
\begin{align*}
BP^2 &= BM^2 + PM^2 - 2 \cdot BM \cdot PM \cdot \cos (\theta/2) \\
&= (AB - AM)^2 + PM^2 - 2 \cdot (AB - AM) \cdot PM \cdot \cos (\theta/2).
\end{align*}Finally, $BC = PC$ gives us
\[AB^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot BC \cdot \cos \theta = AC^2.\]Hence,
\begin{align*}
\frac{AC}{AP} &= \frac{AB^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot BC \cdot \cos \theta}{AP^2} \\
&= \frac{AB^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot BC \cdot \cos \theta}{AN^2 + NP^2 - 2 \cdot AN \cdot NP \cdot \cos (\theta/2)} \\
&= \frac{AB^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot BC \cdot \cos \theta}{(AB - AM)^2 + PM^2 - 2 \cdot (AB - AM) \cdot PM \cdot \cos (\theta/2) + AN^2} \\
&= \frac{1000^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot 1000 \cdot BC \cdot \cos \theta}{(1000 - 17)^2 + PM^2 - 2 \cdot (1000 - 17) \cdot PM \cdot \cos (\theta/2) + 34^2}.
\end{align*}We can compute that $\cos \theta = \frac{1000^2 + 2009^2 - BD^2}{2 \cdot 1000 \cdot 2009} = \frac{1}{2}.$  Also, by the Law of Cosines on triangle $BCD,$ $BD^2 = 1000^2 + 2009^2 - 2 \cdot 1000 \cdot 2009 \cdot \cos \theta = 1000^2 + 2009^2 - 1000 \cdot 2009.$  Hence,
\[BC^2 = BD^2 - CD^2 = BD^2 - AB^2 = 2009^2 - 1000^2.\]Furthermore, by the Law of Cosines on triangle $APM,$
\begin{align*}
PM^2 &= AM^2 + AP^2 - 2 \cdot AM \cdot AP \cdot \cos (\theta/2) \\
&= 17^2 + AP^2 - 2 \cdot 17 \cdot AP \cdot \cos (\theta/2).
\end{align*}Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\frac{AC}{AP} &= \frac{1000^2 + (2009^2 - 1000^2) - 2 \cdot 1000 \cdot (2009^2 - 1000^2) \cdot \frac{1}{2}}{(1000 - 17)^2 + (17^2 + AP^2 - 2 \cdot 17 \cdot AP \cdot \cos (\theta/2)) - 2 \cdot (1000 - 17) \cdot PM \cdot \cos (\theta/2) + 34^2} \\
&= \frac{2009}{\frac{2009 + 17^2 - 2 \cdot 17 \cdot PM \cdot \cos (\theta/2) + 34^2}{2}} \\
&= \frac{2009}{\frac{(2009 + 17^2 + 34^2)/2 - 17 \cdot PM \cdot \cos (\theta/2)}{2}} \\
&= \frac{2009}{\frac{2009 + 17^2 + 34^2}{2} - 17 \cdot PM \cdot \cos (\theta/2)}.
\end{align*}Finally, by the Law of Cosines on triangle $APN,$
\[PM^2 = AN^2 + AP^2 - 2 \cdot AN \cdot AP \cdot \cos (\theta/2) = 34^2 + AP^2 - 2 \cdot 34 \cdot AP \cdot \cos (\theta/2).\]Hence,
\[\frac{AC}{AP} = \frac{2009}{\frac{2009 + 17^2 + 34^2}{2} - 17 \cdot AP \cdot (\cos (\theta/2) - 2 \cdot \cos^2 (\theta/2))}.\]We know $\cos \theta = \frac{1}{2},$ so $\cos (\theta/2) = \frac{\sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2}}}{2}.$  Hence,
\begin{align*}
\frac{AC}{AP} &= \frac{2009}{\frac{2009 + 17^2 + 34^2}{2} - 17 \cdot AP \cdot \left( \frac{\sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2}}}{2} - 2 \cdot \frac{2 + \sqrt{2}}{4} \right)} \\
&= \frac{2009}{\frac{2009 + 17^2 + 34^2}{2} - 17 \cdot AP \cdot \left( \frac{\sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2}}}{2} - \frac{2 + \sqrt{2}}{2} \right)} \\
&= \frac{2009}{\frac{2009 + 17^2 + 34^2}{2} + 17 \cdot AP \cdot \left( \frac{\sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2}}}{2} - \frac{2 + \sqrt{2}}{2} \right)}.
\end{align*}Finally, substituting $AP = \frac{17}{2009} \cdot 2009 = 17,$ we get
\[\frac{AC}{AP} = \frac{2009}{\frac{2009 + 17^2 + 34^2}{2} + 17 \cdot 17 \cdot \left( \frac{\sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2}}}{2} - \frac{2 + \sqrt{2}}{2} \right)} = \boxed{\frac{2009}{170}}.\]

